# Complete Domain & DNS Setup Guide
## Webdev + Cloudflare + Ubuntu Server + Self-Hosted Mail

This guide documents the complete process of configuring a newly registered domain purchased through **Webdev Zimbabwe**. Webdev automatically integrates with Cloudflare, so DNS is managed directly through the Webdev control panel while Cloudflare provides DNS and proxy services behind the scenes.

---

# Architecture

```
                    Internet
                        │
                        ▼
               Webdev Registrar
                        │
          (Automatic Cloudflare Integration)
                        │
                        ▼
                Cloudflare DNS
                        │
        ┌───────────────┴───────────────┐
        │                               │
    Website (HTTPS)                Mail Server
        │                               │
        └──────────── Ubuntu VPS ───────┘
                  Public IP
               16.192.59.194
```

---

# Prerequisites

- Domain purchased through Webdev
- Ubuntu Server (22.04/24.04)
- Static Public IP Address
- SSH Access
- Nginx or Apache
- (Optional) Mail Server (Postfix, Dovecot, Stalwart, Mailcow, etc.)

Example

```
Domain:
blessed.co.zw

Server IP:
16.192.59.194
```

---

# Step 1 - Register the Domain

Purchase the domain through Webdev.

Example

```
blessed.co.zw
```

After payment, wait until the domain status becomes **Active**.

**Note**

For newly registered `.co.zw` domains, DNS propagation and registry delegation may take several hours (sometimes up to 24 hours). During this period:

- WHOIS may show no DNS records.
- BusyRack DNS Manager may display:
  ```
  Domain is invalid or disabled by admin.
  ```
- This is normal while the registry completes the delegation.

---

# Step 2 - Access DNS Management

Since Webdev automatically integrates with Cloudflare, all DNS records are managed from the **Webdev DNS Manager**.

No manual Cloudflare nameserver changes are required.

---

# Step 3 - Configure Website DNS

| Type | Name | Content | Proxy |
|------|------|---------|-------|
| A | @ | 16.192.59.194 | Proxied |
| CNAME | www | blessed.co.zw | Proxied |

The root domain points directly to the server, while `www` is an alias of the root domain.

---

# Step 4 - Configure Mail DNS

Mail records must **not** be proxied.

| Type | Name | Content | Proxy |
|------|------|---------|-------|
| A | mail | 16.192.59.194 | DNS Only |
| MX | @ | mail.blessed.co.zw | DNS Only |

MX Priority

```
10
```

---

# Step 5 - Configure SPF

Add the following TXT record.

| Type | Name | Value |
|------|------|-------|
| TXT | @ | `v=spf1 mx ip4:16.192.59.194 -all` |

This authorizes your server to send mail for the domain.

---

# Step 6 - Configure DMARC

Start with monitoring mode.

| Type | Name | Value |
|------|------|-------|
| TXT | _dmarc | `v=DMARC1; p=none; rua=mailto:dmarc@blessed.co.zw` |

After confirming that SPF and DKIM are working correctly, change the policy to:

```
v=DMARC1; p=quarantine; rua=mailto:dmarc@blessed.co.zw
```

Eventually, you can enforce the strictest policy:

```
v=DMARC1; p=reject; rua=mailto:dmarc@blessed.co.zw
```

---

# Step 7 - Configure DKIM

Your mail server generates the DKIM key.

Example

| Type | Name | Value |
|------|------|-------|
| TXT | default._domainkey | Generated by your mail server |

Example value

```
v=DKIM1; k=rsa; p=MIIBIjANBgkqh...
```

---

# Final DNS Records

| Type | Name | Content | Priority | Proxy |
|------|------|---------|----------|-------|
| A | @ | 16.192.59.194 | | Proxied |
| A | mail | 16.192.59.194 | | DNS Only |
| CNAME | www | blessed.co.zw | | Proxied |
| MX | @ | mail.blessed.co.zw | 10 | DNS Only |
| TXT | @ | `v=spf1 mx ip4:16.192.59.194 -all` | | |
| TXT | _dmarc | `v=DMARC1; p=none; rua=mailto:dmarc@blessed.co.zw` | | |
| TXT | default._domainkey | Generated by mail server | | |

---

# Step 8 - Configure Reverse DNS (PTR)

Cloudflare and Webdev cannot configure PTR records.

Request your VPS or cloud provider to create the following reverse DNS entry:

```
16.192.59.194
```

↓

```
mail.blessed.co.zw
```

This significantly improves email deliverability.

---

# Step 9 - Configure the Firewall

Open the following ports.

## Website

```
80
443
```

## Mail

```
25
465
587
110
995
143
993
```

---

# Step 10 - Configure SSL

Install an SSL certificate on your Ubuntu server.

Example (Nginx)

```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-nginx

sudo certbot --nginx
```

Example (Apache)

```bash
sudo apt install certbot python3-certbot-apache

sudo certbot --apache
```

---

# Step 11 - Install a Mail Server

Supported mail servers include:

- Postfix + Dovecot
- Stalwart Mail Server
- Mailcow
- Docker Mailserver
- iRedMail

Configure SMTP, IMAP, DKIM, and TLS.

---

# Step 12 - Verify DNS

```bash
dig blessed.co.zw

dig www.blessed.co.zw

dig mail.blessed.co.zw

dig MX blessed.co.zw

dig TXT blessed.co.zw

dig TXT _dmarc.blessed.co.zw

dig TXT default._domainkey.blessed.co.zw
```

---

# Step 13 - Test Email

Verify that:

- SPF passes
- DKIM passes
- DMARC passes
- Emails are delivered without being marked as spam

Recommended testing tools:

- MXToolbox
- Mail Tester

